Sad how someone could deny that credit to Tamanend.

Undid revision 981551809 by [[Special:Contributions/Brian W. Schaller|Brian W. Schaller]] ([[User talk:Brian W. Schaller|talk]]) The only official agreement was the Treaty of Shackamaxon, agreeing to share the land in Peace. A King from a far away land with some made up plan holds no value, even if its has only been realized recently. The only Agreement was the Treaty of Shackamaxon.

Switched the positions of the founding names to hopefully reach a peaceful agreement and acceptance. Im sure William Penn wouldve wanted Tamanend included. They even formed a Sons of St. Tammany in his honor, which included Founding Fathers Benjamin Franklin & John Hancock. It was their children and grand childrens generation where the initial agreement fell apart, but still, i think peace is the only possilby outcome we will continue to return to.. Im an optimist.

Tamanend accepted goods to allow William Penn and his people to share the land and the sacred hunting grounds open. "Owning land is like owning the ocean, or the air, no one owns land."
added missing name in the founded section

The previous statement conveyed that the Lenape were non-peaceful, and that the quakers tried to promote peace, when in fact they both were peaceful, and wars broke out due to conflicting ideas of "ownership" and religious intolerance from the religious freedom seeking Quakers, after the death of Tamanend and William Penn. The original statement makes it seem as if Peaceful William Penn & Tamanend and their people broke out into wars, when it was their descendants and newcomers.
